and $\partial_x^\alpha$ and $I_x^\alpha$ denote the fractional derivative and integral. The convention of the branch cut we use is $-\pi<\theta\le\pi$. Left and right Liouville are spatially asymmetric because, in real space, the operations involve an integration on the left and on the right of $x$, respectively (Eqs. (\ref{eq:left_deriv}) - (\ref{eq:right_int})). Feller calculus is odd under parity, and thus it resembles an odd-integer-order calculus. On the other hand, since Riesz calculus is even under parity, its behavior is similar to an even-integer-order calculus. We will use all four of these definitions to derive the AB phase with a gauge field that possesses an anomalous dimension.

We can now formulate the equations of motion. To facilitate such a derivation, we need
the fractional version,
\begin{eqnarray}
\int \psi_1^*\partial^{\alpha}\psi_2 = \int \tilde{\partial}^{\alpha}\psi_1^*\psi_2,
\end{eqnarray}
of integration by parts, where $\tilde{\partial}^{\alpha}$ is the conjugate of $\partial^{\alpha}$. If $\partial^\alpha$ is the left (right) Liouville derivative, its conjugate is the right (left) Liouville derivative \cite{Agrawal2002,Samko1993}. Furthermore, $\tilde{\partial}^{\alpha}_F = - \partial_F^\alpha$ and $\tilde{\partial}^{\alpha}_{RZ} = \partial_{RZ}^\alpha$ \footnote{The integration by parts for Feller and Riesz derivatives follows from the integration by parts for Liouville derivatives and Eqs. \ref{eq:real_feller_deriv} and \ref{eq:real_riesz_deriv}.}. Here the subscripts $F$ and $RZ$ correspond to Feller and Riesz.  Using this integration by parts property, one can derive the equations of motion from this action \cite{lazo2011} as
\begin{eqnarray}
\tilde{\partial}^{\alpha_\mu}_\mu F^{\mu\nu} = J^{\nu}.
\end{eqnarray}
The Bianchi identity,
\begin{eqnarray}
\partial^{\alpha_\mu}_\mu \tilde{F}^{\mu\nu} = 0,
\end{eqnarray}
 arises from the antisymmetry in $F$ (Eq. (\ref{eq:Fdef})) where $\tilde{F}^{\mu\nu} \equiv \epsilon^{\mu\nu\lambda\rho}F_{\lambda\rho}$.
We identify the fractional electric and magnetic fields as $E^i = -F^{0i}$ and $\epsilon^{ijk}B^k = -F^{ij}$ respectively. In 3+1 dimensions, all the Maxwell equations are modified accordingly with fractional derivatives, for example
\begin{eqnarray}
\bm\nabla^{\alpha} \cdot {\bm B} =0
\end{eqnarray}
where $\bm\nabla^\alpha \equiv \{\partial_x^\alpha,\partial_y^\alpha,\partial_z^\alpha\}$.  Because ${\bm \nabla}^\alpha\times {\boldsymbol{A}}={\bm B}$ and $[A_i] = \alpha$, the units of the magnetic field are $[B]=2\alpha$. We will work with the convention that it is the $B-$field that has the anomalous dimension and the charge remains unchanged.  A further consequence of the Maxwell equations is that the continuity equation\cite{lazo2011}
 \begin{eqnarray}
{\bm \nabla}^\alpha \cdot {\bm J} +\partial_t\rho=0
\end{eqnarray}
must involve the fractional derivative.  It is this version of the continuity equation that must be used instead of the traditional one\cite{karchhartnoll} in the context of a current with an anomalous dimension.

We are now set up to calculate the AB phase using fractional calculus. Let us define the covariant derivative $D_i \equiv \partial_i - i\frac{e}{\hbar}a_i$ with the associated gauge connection \cite{hermann}
\begin{eqnarray} \label{eq:defa}
a_i \equiv [\partial_i,I^\alpha_i A_i] = \partial_i I^\alpha_iA_i
\end{eqnarray}
which transforms as $a_\mu \rightarrow a_\mu+\partial_\mu\Lambda$ because the fundamental theorem of fractional calculus\cite{grigoletto} in any of the forms presented earlier guarantees that $I^\alpha\partial^\alpha\Lambda=\Lambda$.
As a result, the Schr\"odinger Lagrangian,
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathcal{L} = \frac{\hbar^2}{2m}D_i\psi^\dagger D_i\psi - i\hbar\psi^\dagger D_t\psi
\end{eqnarray}
is invariant under the  $U(1)$ transformation.  Choosing $A_0=0$, we reduce the Schr\"{o}dinger equation to 
\begin{eqnarray} \label{eq:schromag}
-\frac{\hbar^2}{2m}(\partial_i - i\frac{e}{\hbar}a_i)^2\psi = i\hbar\partial_t\psi.
\end{eqnarray}
To derive the AB phase, let us consider a particle confined on the $x,y$ plane with fractional magnetic field applied along the $z$ axis. Assume a particle can move from point $r_i$ to $r_f$ along path 1 (with wave function $\psi_1$) and along  path 2 (with wave function $\psi_2$). The total wave function at the point $r_f$ at zero fractional magnetic field ($a_i = 0$) is $\psi = \psi_1 + \psi_2$. The total wave function at $r_f$ changes to
\begin{eqnarray}
\psi &=& \exp(i\frac{e}{\hbar}\int\limits_{\mathrm{path \ 1}}\bm a(r')\cdot d\bm l')\psi_1(r_f,t) \nonumber \\ &+& \exp(i\frac{e}{\hbar}\int\limits_{\mathrm{path \ 1}}\bm a(r')\cdot d\bm l')\psi_2(r_f,t) \nonfrenchspacing \\
&=&  C \bigg( \psi_1(r_f,t) + \exp(i\frac{e}{\hbar}\oint \bm a(r')\cdot d\bm l')\psi_2(r_f,t) \bigg). \nonumber \\
\end{eqnarray}
Here $C$ is an over all phase factor $= \exp(i\frac{e}{\hbar}\int\limits_{\mathrm{path \ 1}}\bm a(r')\cdot d\bm l')$. The phase difference between the two paths due to the gauge field is
\begin{eqnarray}
\Delta \phi = \frac{e}{\hbar}\oint \bm a(r')\cdot d\bm l'
\end{eqnarray}

\begin{figure}[h]
	\includegraphics[scale=0.5]{rectangle-1.png}
    \caption{Rectangle geometry that confines particle motion.  The fractional magnetic field is confined to the red region of size $\ell$ in the figure. }
    \label{fig:rectangle}
\end{figure}

To compute this  Aharonov-Bohm phase, we consider two different geometries.  
In Fig. (\ref{fig:rectangle}),  motion is constrained to move along the rectangularly shaped region shown.   The fractional magnetic field is applied along z-axis and is confined to the region of size $\ell\times \ell$ indicated inside the rectangle.  In real space, $\bm B$ takes on the form
\begin{eqnarray}
\bm B(x,y) = B\Theta(\ell^2/4-x^2)\Theta(\ell^2/4-y^2)\hat{z}
\end{eqnarray}
which in momentum space is given by
\begin{eqnarray}
\bm B(\bm k) = B_z(\bm k)\hat{z} = 4B\frac{\sin{\frac{k_x\ell}{2}}\sin{\frac{k_y\ell}{2}}}{k_xk_y}\hat{z}.
\end{eqnarray}
To obtain the AB phase we first solve ${\boldsymbol{B}}(k)=\{F(\alpha,k_x),F(\alpha,k_y),0\} \times {\boldsymbol{A}}(\bm k)$ for ${\boldsymbol{A}}(\bm k)$: 
\begin{eqnarray}
\bm A(\bm k) = \frac{B_z(\bm k)\{-F(\alpha,k_y), F(\alpha,k_x), 0 \}}{F^2(\alpha,k_x)+F^2(\alpha,k_y)}.
\end{eqnarray}
Here the function $F(\alpha,k_i)$ is defined in Eq. (\ref{eq:fraccalc}). All of the different ways of defining the fractional integral come into play in the evaluation of Eq. (\ref{eq:defa}).  In evaluating the subsequent expressions, we find it easiest to work with ${\boldsymbol{b}}=i{\boldsymbol{k}}\times {\boldsymbol{a}}$ which can be written,
\begin{eqnarray}
b_{z,i}=4B\ell^{2\alpha-2}f_i\left(\frac{x}{\ell}\right)f_i\left(\frac{y}{\ell}\right),
\end{eqnarray}
in terms of the function
\begin{eqnarray}
f_i(s)= \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{dz}{2\pi} g_i(z) e^{izs}\sin\frac{z}{2}
\end{eqnarray}
where $g_{1(2)}(z)=i(\pm iz)^{-\alpha}$ for the left (+) and right (-) Liouville calculi, $g_3(z)={\rm sgn}(z)|z|^{-\alpha}$ for the Feller calculus and $g_4(z)=|z|^{-\alpha}$ for the Riesz calculus.  The integral of $b_z(x,y)$,
\begin{eqnarray}
\Delta \phi_{\rm R} = \frac{e}{\hbar} \int\limits_{-a}^{b}dx dy\int\limits_{-c}^{d}b_{z,i}(x,y) 
\end{eqnarray}
in the $x,y$ plane determines the AB phase.  Evaluating all of the integrals, we see that regardless of the fractional calculus used, the AB phase

text:
\begin{align} \label{eq:result_rect}
\Delta\phi_{\rm R}=\begin{cases}
\frac{eB\ell^2}{\hbar}\bigg(\frac{b^{\alpha-1}d^{\alpha-1}}{\Gamma^2(\alpha)} \bigg) & b\gg l, d \gg l\\
\frac{eB\ell^2}{\hbar}\bigg(\frac{a^{\alpha-1}c^{\alpha-1}}{\Gamma^2(\alpha)} \bigg) & a\gg l, c \gg l\\
\frac{eB\ell^2}{\hbar} \bigg( \frac{(a^{\alpha-1}+b^{\alpha-1})(c^{\alpha-1}+d^{\alpha-1})}{4\Gamma^2(\alpha)\sin^2{\frac{\pi\alpha}{2}}} \bigg) & a,b,c,d \gg l\\
\frac{eB\ell^2}{\hbar} \bigg( \frac{(a^{\alpha-1}-b^{\alpha-1})(c^{\alpha-1}-d^{\alpha-1})}{4\Gamma^2(\alpha)\cos^2{\frac{\pi\alpha}{2}}} \bigg) & a,b,c,d \gg l
\end{cases}
\end{align}
